class Solution {
public:
    string robotWithString(string s) {
        int n = s.size();
        vector<int> sufMin(n + 1, 26);
        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; --i) {
            sufMin[i] = min(s[i] - 'a', sufMin[i + 1]);
        }
        string t, res;
        int i = 0;
        while (i < n || !t.empty()) {
            if (t.empty()) {
                t.push_back(s[i++]);
            } else {
                char c = t.back();
                if (i < n && sufMin[i] < (c - 'a')) {
                    t.push_back(s[i++]);
                } else {
                    res.push_back(c);
                    t.pop_back();
                }
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Pre-compute the suffix minima to know the smallest character still in s. Use a stack (string t) to simulate the robot's hand. Whenever the top of t is the smallest remaining character (or tied), pop it to the result; otherwise push the next character from s. This greedy strategy yields the lexicographically smallest string in linear time.

